CONSTITUTION OF INDIA

Part III (Articles 12 — 35)
(Subject to certain conditions, some exceptions
and reasonable restrictions)

guarantees these

Fundamental Rights

Right to Equality

co before law and equal protection of laws;

© irrespective of religion, race, caste, sex or place of birth;
co of opportunity in public employment;

co by abolition of untouchability and titles.

Right to Freedom

oo of expression, assembly, association, movement, residence and profession;

oo of certain protections in respect of conviction for offences;

co of protection of life and personal liberty;

co of free and compulsory education for children between the age of six and fourteen years;
oo of protection against arrest and detention in certain cases.

Right against Exploitation
oo for prohibition of traffic in human beings and forced labour;
co for prohibition of employment of children in hazardous jobs.

Right to Freedom of Religion

oo freedom of conscience and free profession, practice and propagation of religion;

co freedom to manage religious affairs;

co freedom as to payment of taxes for promotion of any particular religion;

co freedom as to attendance at religious instruction or religious worship in educational
institutions wholly maintained by the State.

Cultural and Educational Rights

oo for protection of interests of minorities to conserve their language, script and culture;

co for minorities to establish and administer educational institutions of their choice.

Right to Constitutional Remedies

co by issuance of directions or orders or writs by the Supreme Court and High
Courts for enforcement of these Fundamental Rights.

